WEBVTT

00:09.060 --> 00:13.000
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.640 --> 00:33.960
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.600 --> 00:38.260
And here are your hosts.

00:42.280 --> 00:44.380
This is Daryl Lane and David Cruz.

00:44.840 --> 00:47.640
Poole Anderson is one of a small group of science fiction authors who have written

00:47.640 --> 00:48.380
future histories.

00:48.820 --> 00:52.980
A future history is a group of stories or novels written along a consistent timeline

00:52.980 --> 00:53.620
in the future.

00:54.080 --> 00:58.820
Characters may or may not recur, but the intention is to speculate on the evolution of human

00:58.820 --> 01:00.680
society beyond the present day.

01:01.060 --> 01:03.120
Anderson actually has written two future histories.

01:03.380 --> 01:06.700
The first is not as best known, and it consists of only a dozen or so stories.

01:07.150 --> 01:09.440
Anderson began it in the late 1940s.

01:09.640 --> 01:21.060
But I started out originally rather early in my career and more or less inspired by

01:21.060 --> 01:35.640
the timeline's future history, and constructed one of my own with charts and background material

01:35.640 --> 01:37.420
and so on, like his.

01:37.700 --> 01:42.180
Of course mine was in mind, the events were different.

01:42.180 --> 01:56.460
But basically I wanted to do a similar job that is fictionally tell about the story of

01:56.460 --> 02:07.960
mankind from almost the present day up at least until the early year of expansion among

02:07.960 --> 02:08.680
the stars.

02:09.940 --> 02:16.440
This wasn't going to be the only thing I did by any means, or would write other things

02:16.440 --> 02:24.780
that were not in the series, but from time to time I'd add something to it, and I did

02:24.780 --> 02:25.580
over the years.

02:32.260 --> 02:37.620
Some of the stories in this future history are Wolf, Quixote in the Windmill, Cold Victory,

02:38.040 --> 02:39.640
and the Snows of Ganymede.

02:39.860 --> 02:43.640
The earliest stories in the series describe World War III, which Anderson had said in

02:43.640 --> 02:46.540
1958, a war that destroys modern civilization.

02:47.140 --> 02:49.700
But out of the war decades later rose a new civilization.

02:50.280 --> 02:54.740
It was a repressive one, dominated by the Psycho-Technic Institute, an organization

02:54.740 --> 02:59.600
which strictly plans and controls human progress through psychological manipulation.

03:00.240 --> 03:04.320
Anderson carefully traces out the social, political, and technological events which

03:04.320 --> 03:05.240
shaped the new society.

03:05.240 --> 03:09.780
He describes the colonization of Venus and Mars, for instance, the development of robotics

03:09.780 --> 03:13.440
and artificial regeneration, and the struggle toward a true world government.

03:14.100 --> 03:18.120
In one story, the troublemakers, he sends a space ark off to Alpha Centauri in a voyage

03:18.120 --> 03:19.800
that will take 123 years.

03:20.280 --> 03:22.020
But overall, things don't go smoothly.

03:22.460 --> 03:25.120
Anderson envisions society undergoing many upheavals.

03:25.600 --> 03:29.580
In Quixote in the Windmill, for instance, there are violent anti-robot riots, and in

03:29.580 --> 03:33.500
Cold Victory, a humanist revolution occurs which overthrows a psychotechnic institute.

03:33.500 --> 03:37.680
But some of the institute's people escape to Ganymede, the largest of Jupiter's moons,

03:37.820 --> 03:38.860
where they continue fighting.

03:39.460 --> 03:43.800
It isn't until the story break, the last one in this particular future history, that the

03:43.800 --> 03:45.140
institute is totally wiped out.

03:45.760 --> 03:49.660
At this point, around the 23rd century, the human race is ready to attempt interstellar

03:49.660 --> 03:50.360
colonization.

03:50.820 --> 03:52.980
Anderson leaves it there at the beginning of a new era.

03:53.260 --> 03:55.340
He explains why he added no more to it.

03:56.080 --> 04:04.160
But gradually, for a number of reasons, got less and less interested in continuing and

04:04.160 --> 04:07.120
started phasing it out, doing less and less of it.

04:08.070 --> 04:15.600
One reason for being less interested was that, as for the early part of it, reality was catching

04:15.600 --> 04:16.480
up with me.

04:41.740 --> 04:44.640
Anderson's second future history is much larger and better known.

04:44.640 --> 04:49.420
It includes some of the most memorable characters he's created, like Nicholas von Rhein and Dominic

04:49.420 --> 04:49.840
Flandry.

04:50.140 --> 04:52.540
We'll talk with Anderson about that series next time.

