06:24.200 --> 06:25.080
This is David Cruz.

06:25.380 --> 06:25.980
And Daryl Lane.

06:26.480 --> 06:30.160
Poole Anderson has written one of the most ambitious and extensive future histories in

06:30.160 --> 06:30.800
science fiction.

06:31.200 --> 06:34.760
It's usually called the Future History of the Polysoteknic League, although a better term

06:34.760 --> 06:36.180
might be the League and Empire series.

06:36.540 --> 06:38.760
We asked Anderson how the future history got its start.

06:39.600 --> 06:43.420
Now that has a history much more like that of Topsy.

06:43.660 --> 06:44.340
It just grew.

06:46.380 --> 06:53.280
Originally I'd written a few stories about Nicholas von Rhein and I'd written a few stories

06:53.280 --> 06:57.400
about Dominic Flandry, who lived in completely different miliars, of course.

06:58.680 --> 07:07.360
And then one day on an impulse, I thought, well gosh, they could be on the same timeline,

07:07.360 --> 07:10.020
one living about 500 years after the other.

07:11.200 --> 07:18.680
And through an invention of that in one of the, once, one of the Flandry stories, and

07:18.680 --> 07:24.800
then started fitting in other stories wherever it was convenient.

07:25.340 --> 07:32.800
You see, the thing with the future history is that although each story should, of course,

07:34.000 --> 07:41.180
be readable independently of any others and comprehensible and so on, nevertheless,

07:41.560 --> 07:48.000
if you have a reader who remembers a number of them, the cross connections will add an

07:48.000 --> 07:51.700
extra dimension and thereby a hope at his enjoyment.

07:54.540 --> 07:57.480
So I started doing it that way.

07:59.640 --> 08:03.960
And after a while realized I had a rather large beast by the tail.

08:04.200 --> 08:14.920
If I was going to stay consistent at all, then I had to keep careful notes and I had to develop

08:14.920 --> 08:17.800
a systematic scheme and so on.

08:19.320 --> 08:27.240
And thus over the years one thing led to another until it all became rather elaborate by now

08:27.240 --> 08:38.580
and what includes, I think, something like 40 separate items of which probably at least

08:39.280 --> 08:42.960
a third or so are full dressed novels.

08:44.240 --> 08:48.160
The first story Nicholas Von Ryn turned up in was the novel The Man Who Counts,

08:48.240 --> 08:50.100
which was also issued as The War of the Wingman.

08:50.540 --> 08:52.460
Von Ryn is a nonheroic type.

08:52.460 --> 08:57.460
He's a fat, loudmouthed, cursing schemer who favors good food, drink and creature comforts.

08:58.000 --> 09:01.860
But using his wits he usually conquers all of his foes, human or alien.

09:02.480 --> 09:06.920
He establishes the Polysotectonic League, a trading guild which carries Earth culture throughout the stars.

09:07.400 --> 09:09.900
We asked Anderson if Von Ryn has been popular with readers.

09:10.740 --> 09:18.840
Oh yes, there are some readers who can't stand him but they don't ignore him either.

09:18.840 --> 09:27.360
And as for the rest, he probably is the most popular character I've ever come up with.

09:28.200 --> 09:31.640
Then about 500 years along the timeline of his future history,

09:31.960 --> 09:35.020
Anderson introduces Dominic Flandry, an agent for the Terran Empire.

09:35.440 --> 09:39.540
He turns up in books like Instant Flandry, The Rebel Worlds, Earthman Go Home,

09:39.880 --> 09:41.580
and A Night of Ghosts and Shadows.

09:42.180 --> 09:45.800
The Flandry stories are set in the 31st century and involve the Terran Empire's

09:45.800 --> 09:48.620
struggle with its powerful alien antagonist, the Merseans.

09:49.120 --> 09:50.780
Flandry is the opposite of Von Ryn.

09:51.060 --> 09:56.260
He's smooth, sophisticated, suave, a man who can either fight or scheme with equal style and flair.

09:56.760 --> 09:58.240
He reminds a reader of James Bond.

09:58.700 --> 10:00.760
We asked Anderson if the relationship was intentional.

10:01.660 --> 10:07.200
Oh no, no I've been asked this before and as a matter of fact the first Flandry story

10:07.200 --> 10:11.620
appeared something like 20 years before the first James Bond story did.

10:13.180 --> 10:19.380
If I was modeling on any other character at all, it would probably have had to be somebody like the scene.

10:20.540 --> 10:25.740
Anderson says he probably won't be adding any more to the future history of the Polysotectic League and the Terran Empire,

10:26.060 --> 10:30.420
but there's enough material there already to keep a science fiction reader busy for a long time.

10:30.820 --> 10:32.880
We'll have some more on Pool Anderson next time.

