12:05.040 --> 12:08.220
A number of science fiction authors employ the technique of world building in their stories.

12:08.540 --> 12:11.780
Pool Anderson is one of the best at world building. He explains the term.

12:12.680 --> 12:27.560
The term simply refers to the construction of an imaginary world as a setting for a story in considerable detail.

12:29.300 --> 12:31.480
Now, lots of people have done this.

12:31.480 --> 12:43.020
This is an obvious example, for example, of what would be J.R.R. Tolkien in The Lord of the Rings and related stories.

12:43.760 --> 12:53.060
He constructs an imaginary world in vast detail, complete down to fine points of the various languages spoken and so on.

12:53.900 --> 12:59.620
Anderson's first extensive attempt at world building was the Planet Diomedes, which was a setting for his novel The Man Who Counts.

12:59.620 --> 13:03.920
He meticulously constructs the planet in detail that allows winged intelligent beings.

13:04.420 --> 13:09.080
The atmosphere, for example, is very heavy, which is necessary to support a large flying creature.

13:09.640 --> 13:13.980
Anderson explains why he spends so much time constructing his planets in consistent and careful detail.

13:13.980 --> 13:26.280
After all, we really cannot reasonably expect that any other planet anywhere in the universe will be very much like Earth.

13:27.180 --> 13:34.380
We'll probably be lucky if we find a few where humans can live without artificial help.

13:37.100 --> 13:50.520
And you're certainly not going to have native humans around there, or oak trees, or rabbits, or any other feature that we know here on Earth.

13:53.000 --> 13:59.860
That's just preposterous, I suppose, on the basis of everything we know about the evolution of life here on Earth.

14:03.520 --> 14:11.220
So, in that case, let's try to set up some of the features which are different.

14:12.940 --> 14:24.200
After all, one reason people read science fiction is precisely that they like to get away from the world around them once in a while and escape into something exotic.

14:24.200 --> 14:39.560
And in my opinion, to the extent that this exotic thing can be made at the same time realistic and convincing, the reader is getting his money's worth.

14:45.880 --> 14:52.440
Almost any world constructed by Anderson in his science fiction stories is put together with attention given to basic scientific laws.

14:52.440 --> 14:56.140
Anderson, after all, was a physics student in college and knows his science.

14:56.800 --> 14:59.260
Other authors, Hal Clement and Larry Niven, come to mind.

14:59.580 --> 15:01.000
Practice careful world-building, too.

15:01.640 --> 15:06.600
In fact, Clement says his science fiction novel challenges its readers to find any scientific errors committed by the author.

15:06.940 --> 15:09.980
Clement calls this The Game. Anderson elaborates on it.

15:09.980 --> 15:22.620
The game consists in an author setting up a world or a situation or something as the very best he can and writing a story about it.

15:24.440 --> 15:30.040
And then that's all he can do. He's made his move and that's it.

15:31.340 --> 15:42.800
And readers are free to thereafter to try to figure out from the story exactly what he had in mind and exactly where he may have gone wrong.

15:43.400 --> 15:47.560
So I've gotten some very interesting mail on technical points.

15:47.560 --> 15:58.880
And yes, sometimes they have indicated to me that I've goofed on this or that detail, but alright.

15:59.700 --> 16:01.520
I'm wondering from that, I don't mind.

16:02.380 --> 16:07.320
With Anderson and with other world builders, a reader gets a bonus to accompany an exciting narrative.

16:07.680 --> 16:08.880
Interesting and accurate science.

