17:41.960 --> 17:46.700
Poole Anderson is noted both as a master world builder and as a creator of believable aliens.

17:46.700 --> 17:52.260
He matches aliens to their planets with meticulous and loving care and with great concern for scientific accuracy.

17:52.760 --> 17:59.400
One of the best examples of his talents in this area is the race of winged creatures included in his future history of the Polysotechnic League.

18:00.100 --> 18:08.000
Actually, he constructed two separate races of winged beings, the Diomedians from the Nicholas Von Rhein novel The Man Who Counts and the Ythrians of the planet Avalon.

18:08.420 --> 18:12.600
Anderson explains how he got interested in intelligent beings with the ability to fly.

18:12.600 --> 18:23.680
All the way back when, many years ago, I mean many years ago, it's about 40 by now,

18:25.320 --> 18:32.320
Al Sprague the camp had published an article on intelligent non-human beings,

18:34.060 --> 18:45.100
where he used basic physical principles to demolish a number of notions, you know, like the idea of a giant insect and so on.

18:45.260 --> 18:46.480
It's just impossible.

18:46.760 --> 18:51.060
It would collapse under its own weight because it hasn't got the structure to support that weight.

18:51.060 --> 18:52.420
Things like that.

18:54.020 --> 19:19.200
And one thing he doubted was that you could have an intelligent being which flies because the wing loading that a living flyer can absorb is a take.

19:20.140 --> 19:25.380
It's so small that there just wouldn't be room for a sizable brain.

19:27.080 --> 19:30.800
Anderson thought about the camp's arguments and at last came to at least a partial solution.

19:31.900 --> 19:36.020
Well, science fiction writers tend to take this sort of a thing as a challenge.

19:37.780 --> 19:47.420
And so when I wrote The Man Who Counts quite a while ago, I did have winged intelligent beings,

19:47.420 --> 19:56.260
but I designed a planet such that it had a very dense atmosphere, which of course would make it easier to get about in the air.

19:58.580 --> 20:06.140
I also made them essentially six-limbed so that they could have not only wings but legs and hands.

20:07.960 --> 20:13.500
Well, afterward I got to thinking that had been kind of a cop-out. Couldn't there be some way to do it better?

20:13.500 --> 20:20.280
Could it conceivably be done on an earth-like planet? I couldn't see any way.

20:22.120 --> 20:25.080
The camp's arguments were there and they made sense.

20:26.740 --> 20:30.500
At this point, the famous science fiction editor, John W. Campbell, came to the rescue.

20:31.360 --> 20:37.760
Well, when it happened, the very last time I saw the late John W. Campbell,

20:40.000 --> 20:45.420
I was in New York and visited his office and we went out to lunch together.

20:46.840 --> 20:51.200
This was not long before his death. And we sat there talking.

20:52.540 --> 20:57.280
And during a conversation, Anderson brought up the problem of constructing a large intelligent creature who could fly.

20:57.720 --> 20:59.200
Campbell suggested a way to do it.

21:00.260 --> 21:11.320
And he immediately said, well, suppose it had some sort of light-driven supercharging bellows that would give a tremendous cursive ability.

21:14.160 --> 21:27.380
And I immediately saw that this was a way to power a winged animal, give it sufficient energy that it actually could fly in an atmosphere like our own.

21:29.980 --> 21:32.620
Although it might weigh as much as 100 tons.

21:33.440 --> 21:36.480
So on this hint, Anderson created the Ithrians of the planet Avalon.

21:37.180 --> 21:41.020
The people of the wind is probably the best known of his novels involving the Ithrians,

21:41.380 --> 21:45.280
but Anderson used them in a number of stories in his Polyceo-Technique League Future History.

